SIMPLE: impossibility
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Impossibility
<hw>Im*pos`si*bil"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>;
<plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Impossibilities</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu>
<ety>[L. <ets>impossibilitas</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>impossibilit⟦eacute⟧</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The quality of
being impossible; impracticability.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They confound difficulty with <qex>impossibility</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An impossible thing; that which is not possible;
that which can not be thought, done, or endured.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Impossibilities</qex>! O, no, there's none.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Inability; helplessness.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Latimer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Logical impossibility</b></col>, <cd>a condition or
statement involving contradiction or absurdity; as, that a thing can be
and not be at the same time. See <cref>Principle of
Contradiction</cref>, under <er>Contradiction</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Impossible</ent>⟦br⟧
